WEBVTT

﻿1
00:03:08.146 --> 00:03:11.316
<i>Who am I? You sure you want to know?</i>

2
00:03:11.341 --> 00:03:14.695
<i>The story of my life
is not for the faint of heart.</i>

3
00:03:14.916 --> 00:03:17.798
<i>If somebody said 
it was a happy little tale.</i>

4
00:03:17.823 --> 00:03:22.286
<i>if somebody told you I was just 
an average guy. not a care in the world.</i>

5
00:03:22.311 --> 00:03:24.246
<i>somebody lied.</i>

6
00:03:24.989 --> 00:03:30.359
<i>But let me assure you. this. like any
story worth telling. is all about a girl.</i>

7
00:03:31.029 --> 00:03:35.774
<i>That girl. The girl next door.
Mary Jane Watson.</i>

8
00:03:35.799 --> 00:03:38.886
<i>The woman I've loved 
since before I liked girls.</i>

9
00:03:38.911 --> 00:03:41.581
<i>I'd like to tell you that's me
next to her.</i>

10
00:03:41.740 --> 00:03:43.742
<i>Aw. heck. I'd even take him.</i>

11
00:03:45.222 --> 00:03:47.724
Hey! Stop the bus!

12
00:03:48.725 --> 00:03:50.054
<i>That's me.</i>

13
00:03:50.157 --> 00:03:52.033
Tell him to stop! Please!

14
00:03:52.274 --> 00:03:53.483
Stop!

15
00:03:53.508 --> 00:03:55.820
Hey! Stop the bus!

16
00:03:55.845 --> 00:03:59.298
Stop the bus! 
He's been chasing us since Woodhaven.

17
00:03:59.323 --> 00:04:00.574
Catch a cab. Parker!

18
00:04:04.989 --> 00:04:06.875
Thank you. I'm sorry I'm late.

19
00:04:13.213 --> 00:04:14.506
What a geek!

20
00:04:14.995 --> 00:04:16.804
Don't even think about it.

21
00:04:17.387 --> 00:04:19.132
You're so lame. Parker.

22
00:04:19.585 --> 00:04:21.170
Would you date him?

23
00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:41.140
Midtown High seniors.

24
00:04:41.425 --> 00:04:43.765
No wandering. Proceed direct...

25
00:04:43.790 --> 00:04:45.016
Knock it off.

26
00:04:45.389 --> 00:04:48.515
Remember. it is a privilege to be here.

27
00:04:49.155 --> 00:04:54.515
We're guests of Columbia University's
Science Department. So behave accordingly.

28
00:04:54.956 --> 00:04:58.001
Let's not have a repeat
of our trip to the planetarium.

29
00:04:58.288 --> 00:05:02.859
Come on. stay together. Proceed up 
the steps and into the building.

30
00:05:05.031 --> 00:05:06.992
- Where were you?
- Checking out the library.

31
00:05:07.474 --> 00:05:09.710
- Looking at the books.
- Yeah. right.

32
00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:14.160
Can we drive around the corner. please?

33
00:05:14.184 --> 00:05:17.609
Why? The entrance is right there.

34
00:05:17.634 --> 00:05:21.585
Dad. this is public school. I can't
show up in an field trip in a Rolls.

35
00:05:21.610 --> 00:05:26.929
I should trade my car for a Jetta just
because you flunked out of private school?

36
00:05:26.954 --> 00:05:28.433
It wasn't for me.

37
00:05:28.457 --> 00:05:29.998
Of course it was.

38
00:05:30.865 --> 00:05:32.676
Don't ever be ashamed of who you are.

39
00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:34.531
I'm not ashamed of who I am.

40
00:05:35.427 --> 00:05:36.720
It's just...

41
00:05:36.745 --> 00:05:38.204
Just what. Harry?

42
00:05:38.672 --> 00:05:40.174
Forget it.

43
00:05:43.153 --> 00:05:44.062
Pete!

44
00:05:44.873 --> 00:05:46.570
- Hi. Harry.
- Hey. man. What's up?

45
00:05:46.597 --> 00:05:47.690
Harry!

46
00:05:48.307 --> 00:05:50.460
- Won't you be needing this?
- Thanks. Dad.

47
00:05:51.476 --> 00:05:54.082
Peter. May I introduce my father.
Norman Osborn.

48
00:05:54.104 --> 00:05:55.622
I've heard so much about you.

49
00:05:55.647 --> 00:05:57.090
It's a great honor to meet you. sir.

50
00:05:57.107 --> 00:05:59.318
Harry tells me 
you're quite the science whiz.

51
00:05:59.343 --> 00:06:02.337
I'm something of a scientist myself.

52
00:06:02.362 --> 00:06:05.674
I read all your research on nanotechnology.
Really brilliant.

53
00:06:05.699 --> 00:06:08.744
- You understood it?
- Yes. I wrote a paper on it.

54
00:06:08.952 --> 00:06:12.164
Impressive. 
Your parents must be very proud.

55
00:06:12.189 --> 00:06:14.113
I live with my aunt and uncle.
They are proud.

56
00:06:14.137 --> 00:06:15.460
Hey. you two!

57
00:06:15.792 --> 00:06:17.085
Let's move!

58
00:06:17.110 --> 00:06:18.343
Nice to meet you.

59
00:06:18.587 --> 00:06:20.380
- Hope to see you again.
- Yeah.

60
00:06:23.070 --> 00:06:24.621
He doesn't seem so bad.

61
00:06:24.645 --> 00:06:26.574
Not if you're a genius.

62
00:06:26.623 --> 00:06:28.625
I think he wants to adopt you.

63
00:06:28.821 --> 00:06:33.757
There are over 32.000 known species
of spider in the world.

64
00:06:33.782 --> 00:06:37.578
They're in the order Araneae.
divided into three suborders.

65
00:06:37.603 --> 00:06:38.941
That's amazing!

66
00:06:38.966 --> 00:06:44.320
This is the most advanced electron
microscope on the East Coast. It's unreal.

67
00:06:45.488 --> 00:06:48.534
Arachnids from all three groups possess
varying strengths.

68
00:06:48.559 --> 00:06:51.921
which help them in their constant search
for food.

69
00:06:51.946 --> 00:06:56.570
For example. the Delena spider.
family Sparassidae

70
00:06:56.595 --> 00:07:00.742
has the ability to jump to catch its prey.

71
00:07:00.878 --> 00:07:02.630
For the school paper?

72
00:07:07.232 --> 00:07:14.365
Next. we have the net web spider.
family Filistatidae. genus Kukulcania.

73
00:07:14.392 --> 00:07:19.231
It spins an intricate funnel-shaped web 
whose strands have a tensile strength

74
00:07:19.256 --> 00:07:24.289
proportionately equal to
the high-tension wires used in Bridges.

75
00:07:24.744 --> 00:07:25.777
Leave him alone.

76
00:07:25.801 --> 00:07:26.656
Or what?

77
00:07:26.681 --> 00:07:28.945
Or his father will fire your father.

78
00:07:30.117 --> 00:07:32.594
What's Daddy gonna do? Sue me?

79
00:07:32.619 --> 00:07:34.234
What is going on?

80
00:07:34.746 --> 00:07:37.230
The next person who talks
will fail this course.

81
00:07:37.255 --> 00:07:38.458
I kid you not.

82
00:07:38.483 --> 00:07:40.071
- This spider...
- Let's go.

83
00:07:40.085 --> 00:07:45.032
...hunts using a set of reflexes with
nerve-conduction velocity so fast

84
00:07:45.057 --> 00:07:48.777
that some researchers believe
it almost borders on precognition.

85
00:07:48.802 --> 00:07:50.971
- Those guys are jerks.
- An early awareness of danger.

86
00:07:50.996 --> 00:07:52.837
A spider-sense.

87
00:07:53.494 --> 00:07:55.162
Hey. look at that spider.

88
00:07:55.187 --> 00:07:59.352
Some spiders change colors
to blend into their environment.

89
00:07:59.852 --> 00:08:01.915
It's a defense mechanism.

90
00:08:02.149 --> 00:08:05.586
Peter. what makes you think
I'd want to know that?

91
00:08:05.611 --> 00:08:06.820
Who wouldn't?

92
00:08:06.845 --> 00:08:10.682
Over five painstaking years.
Columbia's research facility...

93
00:08:10.882 --> 00:08:12.614
You gonna talk to her now?

94
00:08:12.638 --> 00:08:15.516
Oh. no. Come on. You talk to her.

95
00:08:15.541 --> 00:08:20.517
With these DNA blueprints. we have
begun what was once thought impossible.

96
00:08:20.542 --> 00:08:22.149
Disgusting.

97
00:08:22.174 --> 00:08:24.196
Yeah. hateful little things.

98
00:08:24.444 --> 00:08:25.820
I love them!

99
00:08:26.043 --> 00:08:27.298
Yeah. me too.

100
00:08:28.849 --> 00:08:35.305
You know. spiders can change their color 
to blend into their environment.

101
00:08:35.330 --> 00:08:36.815
Really?

102
00:08:36.923 --> 00:08:39.383
Yeah. it's a defense mechanism.

103
00:08:40.687 --> 00:08:41.813
- Cool.
- Yeah.

104
00:08:41.838 --> 00:08:44.842
Transfer RNA to encode 
an entirely new genome.

105
00:08:44.867 --> 00:08:48.118
combining the genetic information 
from all three spiders

106
00:08:48.143 --> 00:08:52.712
into these 15 genetically designed
super-spiders.

107
00:08:52.737 --> 00:08:54.239
There's 14.

108
00:08:54.898 --> 00:08:56.415
I beg your pardon?

109
00:08:56.440 --> 00:08:57.821
One's missing.

110
00:08:57.846 --> 00:08:58.946
Yeah.

111
00:09:01.914 --> 00:09:04.610
I guess the researchers
are working on that one.

112
00:09:04.917 --> 00:09:09.962
Do you know that this is the largest
electron microscope on the East Coast?

113
00:09:09.987 --> 00:09:13.712
You were talking throughout
that woman's entire presentation.

114
00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:15.923
Let's talk about how we listen.

115
00:09:20.286 --> 00:09:26.048
I don't know what it's like at those fancy
private schools. but at Midtown High...

116
00:09:34.748 --> 00:09:37.774
Could I take your picture?
I need one with a student in it.

117
00:09:38.584 --> 00:09:40.305
- Sure.
- Great.

118
00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:42.790
Where do you want me? Over here?

119
00:09:42.815 --> 00:09:44.266
Yeah. that's great.

120
00:09:44.507 --> 00:09:46.175
Don't make me look ugly.

121
00:09:46.401 --> 00:09:48.313
That's impossible.

122
00:09:55.838 --> 00:09:56.954
Perfect.

123
00:10:04.557 --> 00:10:06.100
- Is that good?
- Great.

124
00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:13.197
That's great.

125
00:10:18.785 --> 00:10:20.516
M.J.. let's go!

126
00:10:22.164 --> 00:10:23.431
Wait.

127
00:10:23.456 --> 00:10:24.751
Thanks!

128
00:10:38.262 --> 00:10:41.118
Parker. let's do it.

129
00:10:57.740 --> 00:11:01.470
We've solved the horizon glide
and the balance issues.

130
00:11:01.495 --> 00:11:04.039
I've already seen the glider.

131
00:11:04.276 --> 00:11:06.420
That's not what I'm here for.

132
00:11:06.567 --> 00:11:09.076
General Slocum. good to see you again.

133
00:11:10.094 --> 00:11:12.443
Mr. Balkan. Mr. Fargas.

134
00:11:12.468 --> 00:11:14.537
- Norman.
- Mr. Osborn.

135
00:11:14.562 --> 00:11:18.107
Always a pleasure to have our
board of directors pay us a little visit.

136
00:11:18.132 --> 00:11:21.772
I want the progress report on 
human performance enhancers.

137
00:11:21.918 --> 00:11:26.422
We tried vapor inhalation with rodent
subjects. Their strength increased by 800%.

138
00:11:26.447 --> 00:11:28.506
- That's excellent.
- Any side effects?

139
00:11:28.531 --> 00:11:29.740
In one trial. yes.

140
00:11:29.772 --> 00:11:32.751
It was an aberration.
The tests since then have been successful.

141
00:11:32.776 --> 00:11:36.530
In the trial that went wrong.
what were the side effects?

142
00:11:36.555 --> 00:11:38.890
Violence. aggression...

143
00:11:39.537 --> 00:11:40.951
...and insanity.

144
00:11:40.976 --> 00:11:42.276
What do you recommend?

145
00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:43.928
That was only one test.

146
00:11:43.953 --> 00:11:49.744
Except for Dr. Stromm. our staff certifies
the product ready for human testing.

147
00:11:49.768 --> 00:11:51.162
Dr. Stromm?

148
00:11:52.230 --> 00:11:55.256
We need to take the whole line
back to formula.

149
00:11:57.222 --> 00:11:58.455
Back to formula?

150
00:11:58.479 --> 00:11:59.641
Dr. Osborn.

151
00:12:00.794 --> 00:12:02.629
I'll be frank with you.

152
00:12:02.942 --> 00:12:07.780
I never supported your program. We
have my predecessor to thank for that.

153
00:12:07.894 --> 00:12:10.647
Norman. the general gave the go-ahead
to Quest Aerospace

154
00:12:10.662 --> 00:12:13.817
to build a prototype of
their exoskeleton design.

155
00:12:14.064 --> 00:12:15.472
They test in two weeks.

156
00:12:15.496 --> 00:12:22.326
And if your performance enhancers have not
had a successful human trial by that date.

157
00:12:22.351 --> 00:12:26.109
I'm gonna pull your funding.
I'm going to give it to them.

158
00:12:28.382 --> 00:12:30.187
Gentlemen. Ladies.

159
00:12:35.506 --> 00:12:40.928
And the Lord said. "Let there be light."
And voilà! There is light.

160
00:12:41.078 --> 00:12:43.405
Forty soft. glowing watts of it.

161
00:12:43.430 --> 00:12:47.828
Good boy. God will be thrilled.
Just don't fall on your ass.

162
00:12:48.461 --> 00:12:50.913
I'm already on my ass. May.

163
00:12:51.172 --> 00:12:55.834
When the plant's senior electrician
is laid off after 35 years.

164
00:12:55.859 --> 00:12:58.754
what would you call it?
I am on my ass.

165
00:12:58.779 --> 00:13:00.968
Hand me that dish. The green one.

166
00:13:01.279 --> 00:13:06.453
The corporation is downsizing
the people and upsizing their profits.

167
00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:09.390
Oh. Ben. you'll get another job somewhere.

168
00:13:10.624 --> 00:13:13.609
Well. let's look in the paper and see.

169
00:13:14.591 --> 00:13:17.385
There are the want ads.
What do we got here?

170
00:13:17.552 --> 00:13:19.179
Computer...

171
00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:23.362
Computer salesman. computer engineer.
computer analyst.

172
00:13:23.387 --> 00:13:26.999
My Lord. even the computers
need analysts these days.

173
00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:32.913
I'm 68. I'm too old for computers. and
besides. I have a family to provide for.

174
00:13:32.938 --> 00:13:36.041
I love you. And Peter loves you.

175
00:13:36.066 --> 00:13:39.545
You're the most responsible man
I've ever known.

176
00:13:39.570 --> 00:13:43.257
We've been down-and-out before.
But somehow. we survive.

177
00:13:43.281 --> 00:13:44.234
Yeah.

178
00:13:45.075 --> 00:13:46.953
Hi. sweetie. You're just...

179
00:13:47.566 --> 00:13:49.596
Just in time for dinner.

180
00:13:49.620 --> 00:13:52.291
Hey. how you doing. buddy? 
How was the field trip?

181
00:13:52.316 --> 00:13:54.906
I don't feel well. I'm gonna go to sleep.

182
00:13:55.085 --> 00:13:56.254
You won't have a bite?

183
00:13:56.278 --> 00:13:57.830
No. thanks. Had a bite.

184
00:13:57.855 --> 00:14:00.335
Did you get some pictures. Peter?

185
00:14:01.258 --> 00:14:03.913
I gotta crash. Everything's fine.

186
00:14:05.441 --> 00:14:07.026
What's that all about?

187
00:14:28.242 --> 00:14:30.721
In this recombination lab.

188
00:14:30.761 --> 00:14:35.391
we use synthesized transfer RNA
to encode an entirely new genome.

189
00:14:35.416 --> 00:14:38.812
combining the genetic information 
from all three spiders

190
00:14:38.837 --> 00:14:43.328
into these 15 genetically
designed super-spiders.

191
00:14:57.941 --> 00:15:01.399
Dr. Osborn. please.
The performance enhancers aren't ready.

192
00:15:02.141 --> 00:15:04.875
The data just doesn't justify this test.

193
00:15:05.582 --> 00:15:09.551
Now. I'm asking you for the last time.
We can't do this.

194
00:15:09.576 --> 00:15:11.461
Don't be a coward.

195
00:15:11.941 --> 00:15:14.680
Risks are part of laboratory science.

196
00:15:14.906 --> 00:15:18.936
Let me reschedule. with a proper
medical staff and a volunteer.

197
00:15:18.961 --> 00:15:21.421
- Just give me two weeks.
- Two weeks?

198
00:15:21.446 --> 00:15:26.196
In two weeks. we'll have lost the contract
to Quest and OSCORP will be dead.

199
00:15:26.221 --> 00:15:29.055
Sometimes you gotta do things yourself.

200
00:15:29.080 --> 00:15:31.340
Get me the Promachloraperazine.

201
00:15:31.364 --> 00:15:32.092
For what?

202
00:15:32.117 --> 00:15:35.492
It begins catalyzation 
when the vapor hits the bloodstream.

203
00:15:38.619 --> 00:15:44.225
40.000 years of evolution and we've barely
tapped the vastness of human potential.

204
00:15:58.101 --> 00:15:59.435
Oh. that's cold.

205
00:16:58.117 --> 00:16:59.186
Norman?

206
00:17:03.690 --> 00:17:04.930
Norman!

207
00:17:05.942 --> 00:17:06.732
Norman!

208
00:17:15.131 --> 00:17:16.342
Oh. my God.

209
00:17:18.359 --> 00:17:19.777
Oh. my God!

210
00:17:20.123 --> 00:17:21.276
Norman?

211
00:17:22.414 --> 00:17:24.249
Oh. my God! Norman!

212
00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:42.170
Back to formula?

213
00:18:16.862 --> 00:18:18.092
Weird.

214
00:18:29.510 --> 00:18:31.086
- Peter?
- Yeah?

215
00:18:31.111 --> 00:18:32.498
Are you all right?

216
00:18:34.617 --> 00:18:36.244
I'm fine.

217
00:18:36.639 --> 00:18:38.939
Any better this morning? Any change?

218
00:18:38.964 --> 00:18:40.131
Change?

219
00:18:41.284 --> 00:18:43.432
Yep. Big change.

220
00:18:43.457 --> 00:18:46.138
Well. hurry up. You'll be late.

221
00:18:46.163 --> 00:18:47.334
Right.

222
00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:07.137
Okay.

223
00:19:11.235 --> 00:19:12.524
Goodness me!

224
00:19:12.752 --> 00:19:15.802
Jeez. I thought you were sick.

225
00:19:16.187 --> 00:19:17.646
- I got better.
- See?

226
00:19:17.671 --> 00:19:18.455
Bye. guys.

227
00:19:18.479 --> 00:19:20.467
You haven't eaten anything.
Have you got your lunch money?

228
00:19:20.492 --> 00:19:21.303
Yeah. I got it.

229
00:19:21.328 --> 00:19:25.140
Hey. Michelangelo. Don't forget we're
painting the kitchen after school. Got it?

230
00:19:25.165 --> 00:19:27.904
Sure thing. Uncle Ben.
Don't start without me.

231
00:19:27.929 --> 00:19:29.412
And don't start up with me.

232
00:19:31.526 --> 00:19:35.006
Teenagers. Raging hormones.
They never change.

233
00:19:38.010 --> 00:19:40.318
You're trash! You're always
gonna be trash! Just like her!

234
00:19:40.343 --> 00:19:42.318
- I have to go to school.
- Who's stopping you?

235
00:20:01.185 --> 00:20:02.659
Hi. M.J.

236
00:20:03.754 --> 00:20:04.902
Hey. M.J.

237
00:20:05.575 --> 00:20:10.011
I don't know if you realize this. but
we've been neighbors since I was 6.

238
00:20:10.036 --> 00:20:12.784
And I was wondering
if we could get together sometime?

239
00:20:12.809 --> 00:20:15.174
Hey. M.J. I got the car. Hop in.

240
00:20:15.199 --> 00:20:18.253
Do something fun? Or. I don't know.

241
00:20:18.278 --> 00:20:21.222
I thought it'd be time
to get to know each other.

242
00:20:22.514 --> 00:20:23.765
Or not.

243
00:20:29.065 --> 00:20:31.574
Sorry. Parker. the bus is full!

244
00:20:33.311 --> 00:20:35.628
- Stop the bus!
- Catch a cab!

245
00:20:36.366 --> 00:20:37.652
Tell him to stop.

246
00:20:38.644 --> 00:20:40.433
- Check him out!
- Dork!

247
00:21:03.222 --> 00:21:04.399
Dad!

248
00:21:04.901 --> 00:21:06.777
Dad. are you all right?

249
00:21:07.526 --> 00:21:08.819
Harry.

250
00:21:12.272 --> 00:21:14.274
What are you doing on the floor?

251
00:21:14.299 --> 00:21:15.634
I don't know.

252
00:21:16.501 --> 00:21:18.618
Have you been there all night?

